</script>

Text on images is common. And commonly done poorly. Images are busy. Text needs clear background. These two requirements fight like cats and dogs. Here’s how to make them play nice.

## Five Techniques

### 1. Overlay (Scrim)
Add a semi-transparent dark gradient between image and text. The image shows through but at reduced contrast so text wins.

Best for: hero sections, cards with images.

### 2. Text in a Box
Solid or semi-transparent background behind text only, not over the whole image.

Best for: captions, labels, titles in one area.

### 3. Image Darkening
Reduce overall brightness so white text always passes contrast.

Best for: full-screen backgrounds.

### 4. Strategic Positioning
Place text in the intentional blank area: sky, wall, plain background.

Best for: editorial layouts with curated images.

### 5. Text Shadow
Add thick shadow to white text so it reads against any background.

Best for: small use only (captions). Not for headlines.

## Things to Verify

- Always check contrast on the darkest version of the image.
- A gradient scrim should be dark enough that white text passes 4.5:1.
- Never use pure white text on light images without an overlay.
- Text-shadow is a band-aid. Prefer scrim or darkening.
- With animated or changing backgrounds, use even more overlay.

